00:00:43,010 --> 00:00:46,446
is a way for carnivores
to eat a little healthier.

00:00:46,446 --> 00:00:55,889
♪♪

00:00:55,889 --> 00:00:57,958
Hi, Sharks.
My name is Phil Wong.

00:00:57,958 --> 00:00:59,860
And I'm from Brooklyn, New York.

00:00:59,860 --> 00:01:03,230
Let's talk about how
the sausage gets made.

00:01:03,230 --> 00:01:05,933
So many Americans
want to eat less meat,

00:01:05,933 --> 00:01:07,067
whether it's for their health,

00:01:07,067 --> 00:01:09,903
for our planet,
or for animal welfare.

00:01:09,903 --> 00:01:14,174
But it's no secret that most
aren't ready to go vegetarian.

00:01:14,174 --> 00:01:18,879
So why are we stuck
with an all‐or‐nothing choice

00:01:18,879 --> 00:01:20,047
when we go
to the grocery store?

00:01:20,047 --> 00:01:22,849
We thought, why can't we
put veggies <i>and</i> meat

00:01:22,849 --> 00:01:24,818
into a product
that people would love?

00:01:24,818 --> 00:01:26,987
Well, Sharks,
that's where we come in.

00:01:26,987 --> 00:01:29,890
We're meeting in the middle.

00:01:29,890 --> 00:01:32,793
Introducing Misfit Foods,

00:01:32,793 --> 00:01:35,095
a line of delicious sausages

00:01:35,095 --> 00:01:38,231
that are half chicken
and half veggies and spices.

00:01:38,231 --> 00:01:41,835
Our three flavors
will knock your socks off.

00:01:41,835 --> 00:01:43,937
And they're made
with sustainability in mind,

00:01:43,937 --> 00:01:45,305
helping people eat less meat

00:01:45,305 --> 00:01:48,208
by putting more delicious food
on the dinner table,

00:01:48,208 --> 00:01:51,545
because we believe
that change can taste good,

00:01:51,545 --> 00:01:52,913
one link at a time.

00:01:52,913 --> 00:01:55,649
So, Sharks, don't miss out
on this one.

00:01:55,649 --> 00:01:58,752
250K for 5% of our company.

00:01:58,752 --> 00:01:59,720
Wow.

00:01:59,720 --> 00:02:00,954
Sharks, in front of you,

00:02:00,954 --> 00:02:03,690
we have our sausages
prepared three different ways.

00:02:03,690 --> 00:02:04,891
The first is my favorite.

00:02:04,891 --> 00:02:07,094
It's our Sweet Potato Andouille
mac and cheese.

00:02:07,094 --> 00:02:09,096
Next,
our Kale Chimichurri tacos.

00:02:09,096 --> 00:02:11,898
And last is a classic
squash Italian

00:02:11,898 --> 00:02:13,967
on a bun with the fixings.

00:02:13,967 --> 00:02:16,970
Greiner: Wow.
The Citrus Kale is delicious.

00:02:16,970 --> 00:02:18,972
Thank you.
I'm so glad to hear it, Lori.
Really good.

00:02:18,972 --> 00:02:21,074
One thing that I noticed
that I really like

00:02:21,074 --> 00:02:23,210
is that your sodium
is lower

00:02:23,210 --> 00:02:26,546
than the typical
chicken sausages that I buy.

00:02:26,546 --> 00:02:27,114
And the other thing, too,

00:02:27,114 --> 00:02:29,116
is that we have about
40% less cholesterol

00:02:29,116 --> 00:02:31,251
than your typical
chicken sausage, as well.

00:02:31,251 --> 00:02:34,221
And that's something that
our consumers really care about.

00:02:34,221 --> 00:02:36,323
Phil, who's the market
you're going after?

00:02:36,323 --> 00:02:39,760
Like, are you trying to get
people that are meat eaters

00:02:39,760 --> 00:02:41,762
to eat less meat?

00:02:41,762 --> 00:02:42,996
Absolutely,
and, you know,

00:02:42,996 --> 00:02:45,165
I think the proof
is kind of in the pudding.

00:02:45,165 --> 00:02:47,200
We're in our first full year
in market right now,

00:02:47,200 --> 00:02:49,903
and we're on track
for $1.2 million in sales.

00:02:49,903 --> 00:02:51,004
‐Wow.
‐Wow.

00:02:51,004 --> 00:02:53,240
And so, you know,
a good portion of those people

00:02:53,240 --> 00:02:55,809
are just, you know,
your pure carnivores.

00:02:55,809 --> 00:02:57,744
What's your actual sales
to date?

00:02:57,744 --> 00:03:00,147
So we've done
just under 800K to date.

00:03:00,147 --> 00:03:02,816
How are you selling it,
direct or through retail?

00:03:02,816 --> 00:03:04,785
We're about 20%
brick and mortar,

00:03:04,785 --> 00:03:07,087
and that's Whole Foods,
and 80% online.

00:03:07,087 --> 00:03:09,222
How did you come up with this?
What's your background?

00:03:09,222 --> 00:03:12,859
So, you know, food's always been
a really huge part of my life.

00:03:12,859 --> 00:03:14,227
I grew up in a family
of immigrants.

00:03:14,227 --> 00:03:18,832
So my mom is from Indonesia.
My dad is from Macao.

00:03:18,832 --> 00:03:20,967
And so my connection
to Indonesia and Macao

00:03:20,967 --> 00:03:23,170
when I was growing up
was through food.

00:03:23,170 --> 00:03:25,072
And when I got to college
at Georgetown,

00:03:25,072 --> 00:03:27,040
I started learning more
about just, like,

00:03:27,040 --> 00:03:31,578
how huge our environmental
footprint is with our food.

00:03:31,578 --> 00:03:32,279
So I started wondering,

00:03:32,279 --> 00:03:35,982
was there a way to use delicious
food to help the environment?

00:03:35,982 --> 00:03:39,352
And so I started Misfit in
the kitchen that I was sharing

00:03:39,352 --> 00:03:42,456
with the six other guys
I was living with at the time.

00:03:42,456 --> 00:03:43,023
Really?

00:03:43,023 --> 00:03:44,825
Yeah, they weren't
too happy about it.

00:03:44,825 --> 00:03:46,860
Did you raise money
to do this?

00:03:46,860 --> 00:03:49,129
Yeah. So we've raised
$2 million to date.

00:03:49,129 --> 00:03:51,031
‐Hello.
‐Wow.
‐What?

00:03:51,031 --> 00:03:53,667
We're here to not hit
a single or a double, right?

00:03:53,667 --> 00:03:54,935
We're here to hit a home run.

00:03:54,935 --> 00:03:57,170
So what was your last valuation
of the company at?

00:03:57,170 --> 00:03:59,973
So the last valuation
was $4 million.

00:03:59,973 --> 00:04:01,742
Well, we haven't
even talked about

00:04:01,742 --> 00:04:03,110
what it sells for
and what it costs yet.

00:04:03,110 --> 00:04:06,646
So typically, we're selling
for $4.13 a unit

00:04:06,646 --> 00:04:07,714
to the grocery store.

00:04:07,714 --> 00:04:10,717
Our cost is about
$2.91 a unit.

00:04:10,717 --> 00:04:11,952
Okay, so that's
your biggest challenge.

00:04:11,952 --> 00:04:13,887
‐And what do they sell it for?
‐What do they retail it at?

00:04:13,887 --> 00:04:16,523
And so they're retailing it
for anywhere from $5.99

00:04:16,523 --> 00:04:17,991
to $7.99 a unit.

00:04:17,991 --> 00:04:20,861
Now, our gross margins work out
to about 29%.

00:04:20,861 --> 00:04:22,262
What's really important
to know about that

00:04:22,262 --> 00:04:24,798
is that we hit break even
in May of this year,

00:04:24,798 --> 00:04:25,932
and I think that points
to the fact

00:04:25,932 --> 00:04:28,301
that we don't have to
market this product a ton

00:04:28,301 --> 00:04:31,805
and, you know, spend a bunch on
slotting fees, promotional fees

00:04:31,805 --> 00:04:33,106
to get people
to buy this product.

00:04:33,106 --> 00:04:35,308
Are you spending money
on marketing today?

00:04:35,308 --> 00:04:39,146
Very little. It's less
than 5% of our first revenue.
Good for you.

00:04:39,146 --> 00:04:41,815
The refrigerated
and frozen categories

00:04:41,815 --> 00:04:44,785
have eluded me
in making a lot of money.

00:04:44,785 --> 00:04:46,119
I've made investments
in it.

00:04:46,119 --> 00:04:48,655
It's burned up
a lot of my hours,

00:04:48,655 --> 00:04:49,923
which is valuable to me,

00:04:49,923 --> 00:04:52,626
and I haven't really had
a huge hit with it yet.

00:04:52,626 --> 00:04:54,261
I'm out.

00:04:55,262 --> 00:05:00,867
I'm a vegetarian,
and I think it's innovative,

00:05:00,867 --> 00:05:02,936
but I don't know
if I believe in the trend.

00:05:02,936 --> 00:05:04,638
I think consumers
want to go

00:05:04,638 --> 00:05:07,107
one way or another.

00:05:07,107 --> 00:05:11,678
You might be right,
but I don't share that vision.

00:05:11,678 --> 00:05:12,913
I'm out.

00:05:12,913 --> 00:05:13,980
Thank you, Robert.

00:05:13,980 --> 00:05:16,116
So your valuation
seems a little bit rich.

00:05:16,116 --> 00:05:20,253
Mr. Wonderful, could you, like,
soften him up for me?

00:05:20,253 --> 00:05:22,989
‐Soften him up?
‐Well, I would gladly do that.

00:05:22,989 --> 00:05:25,125
O'Leary: I mean, you've
obviously done multiple rounds

00:05:25,125 --> 00:05:29,062
at valuations
lower than this.

00:05:29,062 --> 00:05:30,764
And then you come
in the Shark Tank

00:05:30,764 --> 00:05:32,899
to get a premium investor

00:05:32,899 --> 00:05:36,136
and charge them a premium,
which is not correct,

00:05:36,136 --> 00:05:39,873
because a Shark brings value
that an ordinary investor can't.

00:05:39,873 --> 00:05:41,708
Could you add
"Shame on you"?

00:05:41,708 --> 00:05:42,809
If you want to get
an investor,

00:05:42,809 --> 00:05:44,010
you're gonna have to
take a haircut.

00:05:44,010 --> 00:05:47,681
That's what's gonna happen.
I'm gonna give you...

00:05:47,681 --> 00:05:51,918
$250,000 for 15%.

00:05:51,918 --> 00:05:53,854
And I'm thinking
that's generous.

00:05:53,854 --> 00:05:55,255
Well, there's
your first haircut.

00:05:55,255 --> 00:05:57,157
Man, I shaved my head
like two weeks ago.

00:05:57,157 --> 00:05:59,259
I can't afford
to lose any more of this.
[ Laughs ]

00:05:59,259 --> 00:06:02,863
Greiner: I think good product
speaks for itself, right?

00:06:02,863 --> 00:06:04,064
It's gonna sell.

00:06:04,064 --> 00:06:07,968
I do wonder if people will start
knocking you off like crazy.

00:06:07,968 --> 00:06:09,803
I think it's so smart

00:06:09,803 --> 00:06:11,938
that I think you kind of
have to race to the market.

00:06:11,938 --> 00:06:12,906
Lubetzky:
Mm‐hmm. Mm‐hmm.

00:06:12,906 --> 00:06:16,076
So I'm gonna
give you an offer.

00:06:16,076 --> 00:06:20,914
It's gonna be
a little bit sharkier.

00:06:20,914 --> 00:06:23,917
I'm gonna go $250,000,

00:06:23,917 --> 00:06:27,754
but I'm gonna ask
for 18%.

00:06:27,754 --> 00:06:29,022
Lori,
thank you for that offer.

00:06:29,022 --> 00:06:30,824
Thank you, Lori.
Okay, so let's
talk about this, Phil.

00:06:30,824 --> 00:06:32,726
Phil, let me ask
a couple questions.
Yeah.

00:06:32,726 --> 00:06:34,094
Do you think
you have too many SKUs?

00:06:34,094 --> 00:06:36,229
Because that's
a challenge ‐‐

00:06:36,229 --> 00:06:39,032
you know, trying to get
just that much shelf space.

00:06:39,032 --> 00:06:41,167
Like, for me,
if I was a flexitarian,

00:06:41,167 --> 00:06:43,837
these would have ‐‐
this would be too much, right?

00:06:43,837 --> 00:06:46,072
I'm not a curry guy
and I'm not ‐‐

00:06:46,072 --> 00:06:47,974
Citrus Kale,
maybe I'll try it.

00:06:47,974 --> 00:06:51,811
But, you know,
if it was simpler ‐‐

00:06:51,811 --> 00:06:53,213
I just want a sausage,
you know,

00:06:53,213 --> 00:06:55,949
where I could put it on a bun
and eat it at a cookout

00:06:55,949 --> 00:06:57,884
and know it's healthier
and lower‐calorie.

00:06:57,884 --> 00:06:59,286
Lubetzky:
Mark, you're so right.

00:06:59,286 --> 00:07:03,089
This is incredibly important
for people to understand.

00:07:03,089 --> 00:07:05,292
Every time my team
and I innovate

00:07:05,292 --> 00:07:09,195
and we come up with all these
esoteric ideas, they're fun,

00:07:09,195 --> 00:07:12,933
but they will never beat
the working horse.

00:07:12,933 --> 00:07:15,869
And many entrepreneurs are
trying so hard to differentiate

00:07:15,869 --> 00:07:17,837
and they don't build
that working horse.

00:07:17,837 --> 00:07:20,206
Are you willing to do
just a workhorse product?

00:07:20,206 --> 00:07:22,242
I had no idea you were
a chef, Mark ‐‐ no idea.

00:07:22,242 --> 00:07:24,911
I'm not a chef, but I know
how to dominate markets.

00:07:24,911 --> 00:07:26,680
Are you gonna
make an offer?

00:07:26,680 --> 00:07:33,687
♪♪

00:07:40,694 --> 00:07:42,228
Narrator: Two Sharks are out.

00:07:42,228 --> 00:07:45,065
Phil has offers on the table
from Daniel and Lori

00:07:45,065 --> 00:07:48,501
for his half‐chicken,
half‐veggie sausage company,

00:07:48,501 --> 00:07:49,669
Misfit Foods,

00:07:49,669 --> 00:07:51,838
but Mark may also be interested.

00:07:51,838 --> 00:07:54,441
Are you gonna make an offer?
Cuban: Yes.

00:07:57,177 --> 00:08:00,547
So do you want to try
to do something together?

00:08:00,547 --> 00:08:02,882
Okay, so...

00:08:02,882 --> 00:08:06,786
How about $250,000 for 15%,
two Sharks.

00:08:06,786 --> 00:08:09,689
Two of us.

00:08:09,689 --> 00:08:10,890
Never has
happened before.

00:08:10,890 --> 00:08:12,959
Wow.
This is the first time
we're getting married.

00:08:12,959 --> 00:08:15,895
You're getting a haircut
no matter what happens.

00:08:15,895 --> 00:08:18,198
So, Phil,
that takes your valuation

00:08:18,198 --> 00:08:20,066
from $5 million
you walked in with

00:08:20,066 --> 00:08:22,936
down to $1.6 million,
but you get two Sharks

00:08:22,936 --> 00:08:25,405
and a chef to tell you
what to put in the sausage

00:08:25,405 --> 00:08:27,307
that doesn't eat meat.
